---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'About latepaycalc.com';
const description = 'About the team behind latepaycalc.com — how we calculate B2B invoice late fees and employment final-paycheck penalties, our editorial standards, and how the site is funded.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>About latepaycalc.com</h1>
  <p>latepaycalc.com is a free late-payment resource maintained by The Click Lab. Our calculator and guides cover two distinct situations that share a name but little else: business owners and freelancers trying to work out what a customer owes them in interest and late fees on an overdue invoice, and employees trying to work out what a former employer owes them in statutory penalties for a final paycheck that arrived late. The Site is built to give both groups a plain-English starting number before they send a demand letter, file a wage claim, or call a lawyer &mdash; not a substitute for legal or financial advice.</p>

  <h2>What we do</h2>
  <p>We translate two different bodies of law into plain-English calculators and guides: contract and commercial-interest principles for overdue invoices, and state wage-and-hour statutes for final-paycheck penalties. Every page is reviewed by our <a href="/editorial/">editorial team</a> with citations to the relevant state statutes, agency guidance, and case law. The invoice calculator applies whatever rate your contract specifies, or falls back to a state statutory rate for commercial debts if it doesn't; the final-paycheck calculator applies the specific penalty formula your state uses &mdash; which ranges from California's daily-wage waiting-time penalty to flat liquidated damages in other states, to no statutory penalty at all in a few.</p>

  <h2>Who this calculator is for</h2>
  <p>On the invoice side, most visitors are freelancers, contractors, and small-business owners chasing a customer who hasn't paid on time, trying to figure out what late fee or interest they can legitimately add before sending a follow-up invoice or a demand letter. On the wage side, most visitors are workers who quit or were let go and whose final paycheck was late, short, or never arrived, trying to understand whether their state provides a penalty on top of the wages themselves &mdash; and how large that penalty realistically is. We also see HR and payroll staff double-checking a separation date against their state's deadline before it becomes a claim. We built the Site around these use cases, which is why every guide leads with a plain-English answer before it gets into statutory detail.</p>

  <h2>How the estimate is built</h2>
  <p>The full mechanics &mdash; the invoice interest formula, the rate-priority order used when a contract is silent, the state-by-state final-paycheck penalty structures, and worked examples for both &mdash; are documented on our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>. At a high level: for invoices, the calculator adds any flat late fee to simple daily interest at the contractual, statutory, or judgment rate, in that order of priority. For final paychecks, it applies the selected state's own penalty mechanism &mdash; a per-day wage penalty, a flat multiple of unpaid wages, or nothing at all &mdash; rather than a single national rule, because the two dozen or so states with an actual penalty structure genuinely don't agree with each other.</p>

  <h2>What we don't do</h2>
  <p>We don't provide legal or financial advice, and reading this Site doesn't create an attorney-client relationship. Real invoice disputes depend on the exact contract language, applicable usury limits, and whether a good-faith dispute exists; real wage claims depend on the state, the separation type, and the employer's own records &mdash; details no calculator can fully account for. We also don't evaluate individual disputes, review specific settlement or demand-letter numbers, or file wage claims on anyone's behalf. Separately, the homepage includes an optional case-review form for the final-paycheck side of this Site that connects workers who want their situation evaluated with attorneys &mdash; that's a disclosed paid referral, not editorial content, and using it is always optional (see our <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a>). For your specific situation, consult a licensed attorney or your state's wage enforcement agency; see our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> for pointers on finding the right one.</p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <p>Every guide and reference page is written from primary sources &mdash; state labor codes, commercial-interest and usury statutes, wage-agency guidance, and appellate case law &mdash; and reviewed before publication. We don't publish thin content: each page is meant to answer a specific question a freelancer, small-business owner, or worker would actually ask, with enough detail and enough worked examples to be genuinely useful. Our full editorial workflow, contributor backgrounds, and sourcing policy are on the <a href="/editorial/">editorial team page</a>.</p>

  <h2>How we make money</h2>
  <p>Display advertising via Google AdSense. We don't accept paid placements in our editorial content, and no collection agency or payroll company pays for placement or a favorable mention in our guides. Separately, we offer an optional case-review form on the homepage: if you submit it, your information is shared with attorneys who may compensate The Click Lab Agency LLC for the referral. That's a disclosed advertising product, separate from our editorial content, and using it is always optional. See our <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a> for details on data handling, including exactly what's shared if you use that form.</p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>Questions, corrections, or feedback: see our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
